  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Exploring the Transnational Neighbourhood\" published by Leuven University Press in 2022, demonstrates a significant potential for commercialization, with evidence of listings on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads. The book's focus on sustainability and policy is highlighted by its relevance to global sustainable development goals.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The scholarly work \"Exploring the Transnational Neighbourhood\" showcases the intricacies of transnational dynamics within communities. While the book lacks direct academic citations to date, it provides a foundation for future discourse and analysis in its field, particularly after being published by a reputable academic institution like Leuven University Press in 2022.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">One of the notable aspects of the publication is the strong commercial potential it presents, indicated by the presence of the work on platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads. This commercial linkage, with a strength rating of 0.9, suggests that the book has garnered enough interest to be featured in important online retail venues, highlighting its accessibility and reach to a broader audience beyond academia.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, the publication acknowledges its contributions to sustainability and policy discourse, as evidenced by its affiliation with one of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). This alignment with global initiatives underscores the book's relevance in addressing pressing social issues, even as formal citations and online discussions remain absent at present.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As \"Exploring the Transnational Neighbourhood\" continues to engage with the themes of community and transnationalism, its foundational insights pave the way for future research. The absence of citations thus far might change as more scholars become aware of its thematic contributions, indicating a potential growth in academic interest and utilization in subsequent works.</p>",
